The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt during the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of the world's major developed economies' leaders, no one can say which of them will be part of the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even with German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could become the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has been going on for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend apparently was towards convergence and people seemed to consume the same products everywhere.
McDonald's illustrated this kind of globalization: burning down stores of this chain has become a standard form of protest against globalization.
But lately, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is increasingly interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand foreigners less.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are increasingly sophisticated), companies are relocating their production closer to the markets where goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
Such "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded by Japanese cars. They then began to produce these cars domestically.
Currently, most "Japanese" automobiles sold in the United States are manufactured in the United States. However, reversing the globalization of goods is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotic engineering and the development of processes such as 3D printing.
Thus, the current critique of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
But this evolution reflects not only the slowdown in trade growth.
Consumers in wealthy countries are much more comfortable with foreign products, and in some cases are even dependent on them, from constantly updated electronics and the "ephemeral" low-cost fashion that has become predominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, today's opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
The disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on the issues of obscure courts protecting the interests of foreign companies and supposed to undermine national sovereignty.
Next comes the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, anxiety about this influx may be a precursor to a broader rejection of immigration from failed and impoverished states.
Why are the populations of advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
It's not as if they have never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries constantly travel to distant destinations and hundreds of millions of people from around the world head each year to advanced countries.
The problem lies in the way we travel.
Today, we are more likely to experience things quickly and superficially, rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches us, a single interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper foundation of understanding or cooperation.
Continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach of current travel is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are reluctant to provide good or even simply honest service to people who surely will never return.
Restaurants serve mediocre (or worse) food without a smile, taxi drivers cheat you, hoteliers lie about their facilities.
Furthermore, this little game can suffer interruptions.
On sites where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it has also become a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
Some attacks in places like Bali or the Red Sea tourist complexes are enough to cause a deep economic destabilization.
Tourism companies respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The emblem of modern tourism is a gigantic cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (to visit a beautiful Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new ship Harmony of the Seas by Royal Caribbean aims to reproduce all the climates of the world.
In fact, this ship, which is over 30 meters long and taller than the Eiffel Tower, contains a tropical park and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Bus and train tourist companies do the same to ensure the safety of their clients, releasing them onto a famous site only for a limited time, in fact just long enough to take a few photos.
This style of travel exerts a constraint on the capacity of local infrastructure.
There is often not enough space to walk along the canals of Venice or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual misunderstanding.
Visitors remain within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, meeting only scammers, who offer them trinkets or overpriced taxi rides.
The indigenous people do not particularly appreciate tourist groups gathering around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor maintains any relationship of trust.
It is easy to feel some nostalgia for the time when tourism went hand in hand with long stays and extended encounters with very different cultures.
It would obviously be impossible, for the current number of visitors, to spend weeks or months staying in ancient monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
Airbnb, for example, can provide a much more attractive experience than a hotel or, worse, than a cruise ship.
Is there a policy equivalent to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7, living and working for an extended period of time in a foreign country?
Shortly after the United States entered the war during World War II, Winston Churchill made this famous gesture of lifting camp to stay at the White House for 24 days, in order to strengthen the transatlantic alliance of Britain, deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the greatest enemy of current anti-globalist populists.
